72
00:14:50,727 --> 00:14:53,030
[SPEAKER_02]: Give me one moment.

73
00:14:59,844 --> 00:15:04,608
[SPEAKER_02]: 25189, amendment to Chapter 2, Article 5, Division 2, Medford Standard Compensation Ordinance.

74
00:15:07,480 --> 00:15:10,622
[SPEAKER_02]: In City Council, April 28th, 2026, approved for first reading.

75
00:15:10,842 --> 00:15:14,664
[SPEAKER_02]: To be advertised May 14th, 2026, Medford Transcript and South Marble Journal.

76
00:15:14,684 --> 00:15:19,687
[SPEAKER_02]: It was advertised and it's in City Council, June 9th, 2026, eligible for third reading.

77
00:15:20,207 --> 00:15:31,334
[SPEAKER_02]: This is the standard compensation ordinance which is to create a wage floor for the folks in janitorial and security services who are not otherwise covered

78
00:15:33,714 --> 00:15:35,635
[SPEAKER_02]: prevailing wage schedules of the state.

79
00:15:35,755 --> 00:15:41,836
[SPEAKER_02]: They were exempted, and that means that cities can pay these folks less than the prevailing wage for the work that they do.

80
00:15:42,497 --> 00:15:45,518
[SPEAKER_02]: There are a number of things in this ordinance.

81
00:15:46,318 --> 00:15:49,939
[SPEAKER_02]: The main purpose of it, as we discussed at first reading, is to

82
00:15:51,463 --> 00:16:01,931
[SPEAKER_02]: create a system for a wage floor and fair wages and benefits for the contracted services that our city contracts out for our buildings.

83
00:16:02,091 --> 00:16:05,634
[SPEAKER_02]: And right now that is mainly our janitorial services.

84
00:16:06,114 --> 00:16:07,275
[SPEAKER_02]: There's a lot of history here.

85
00:16:07,295 --> 00:16:13,680
[SPEAKER_02]: This was first proposed in December after some serious concerns about some

86
00:16:14,720 --> 00:16:31,343
[SPEAKER_02]: harmful impacts on folks who had been working for the city in janitorial services at Medford Public Schools, folks who lost their jobs, folks who were really put in very difficult situations because our city doesn't have an ordinance like this.

87
00:16:32,403 --> 00:16:41,905
[SPEAKER_02]: And really, you know, one of the most important things that this ordinance will provide for our city is more certainty.

88
00:16:45,100 --> 00:16:52,949
[SPEAKER_02]: in how we are procuring these kinds of services and more stability in making sure that we get good services on the market.

89
00:16:53,289 --> 00:16:54,891
[SPEAKER_02]: So that is just something that is.

90
00:16:56,992 --> 00:17:07,097
[SPEAKER_02]: It's essential not only from like a values perspective and a morals perspective that when the city is contracting out work, we are paying fair wages and benefits to the people who are doing that work.

91
00:17:07,478 --> 00:17:18,003
[SPEAKER_02]: But it is also important for the city that we are having good services, stable services, the services that we need to keep our buildings clean and well-maintained.

92
00:17:19,024 --> 00:17:21,525
[SPEAKER_02]: So that is the purpose of this ordinance over the last,

93
00:17:23,066 --> 00:17:26,850
[SPEAKER_02]: month and a half since the first reading.

94
00:17:26,870 --> 00:17:30,454
[SPEAKER_02]: I did have some meetings with the city administration.

95
00:17:31,935 --> 00:17:34,738
[SPEAKER_02]: We have made some, we've had good discussions.

96
00:17:35,138 --> 00:17:36,600
[SPEAKER_02]: We've made some progress.

97
00:17:37,100 --> 00:17:40,224
[SPEAKER_02]: I do wanna read a letter from the administration.

98
00:17:40,244 --> 00:17:43,127
[SPEAKER_02]: Give me one second to find it.

99
00:17:51,745 --> 00:17:53,406
[SPEAKER_02]: I don't know why it's not showing up here.

100
00:17:54,967 --> 00:17:56,848
[SPEAKER_02]: And I know that the administration might have.

101
00:18:01,191 --> 00:18:02,452
[SPEAKER_02]: Yes, Chief of Staff.

102
00:18:03,833 --> 00:18:04,533
[SPEAKER_01]: Thank you, President Behrs.

103
00:18:04,573 --> 00:18:14,380
[SPEAKER_01]: I just want to note that Paul Ruggie's on the line and could potentially communicate the communication that was sent over to the council, to yourself and then to the council as well.

104
00:18:14,460 --> 00:18:14,780
[SPEAKER_02]: Sure.

105
00:18:14,800 --> 00:18:15,881
[SPEAKER_01]: If that's easier.

106
00:18:16,421 --> 00:18:18,402
[SPEAKER_02]: If that's the preference, if that's your preference.

107
00:18:18,422 --> 00:18:19,043
[SPEAKER_02]: Sure.

108
00:18:20,166 --> 00:18:23,428
[SPEAKER_02]: Paul, if you would want to read the letter that you sent over today, I'll recognize you.

109
00:18:28,652 --> 00:18:29,753
[SPEAKER_05]: Thank you, President Behrs.

110
00:18:33,571 --> 00:18:53,463
[SPEAKER_05]: This letter came is coming from myself and Fiona Maxwell, the our director of procurement, we are respectfully requesting that the council postpone final passage of the proposed standard compensation ordinance on June 9 to allow additional time for the working group consisting of President bears.

111
00:18:54,424 --> 00:19:15,172
[SPEAKER_05]: Attorney Janelle Austin, Chief of Staff Nina Nazarian, and the undersigned, myself and Fiona, to complete its review and finalize any recommended amendments to ensure that the terms of this ordinance are clearly defined, able to be implemented, enforceable, and minimize liability to the City.

112
00:19:16,212 --> 00:19:26,338
[SPEAKER_05]: As you know, the school department's cleaning services vendor has been notified that the city is exercising year two of the existing contract, extending services through June 30th, 2027.

113
00:19:28,419 --> 00:19:41,666
[SPEAKER_05]: Additionally, the city's cleaning services contract is being extended through June 30th, 2027 through FAC 114, which is the state contract as the procurement method.

114
00:19:42,694 --> 00:19:58,603
[SPEAKER_05]: With both contracts secured for FY 2027, the group is in a good position to continue evaluating the proposed amendments and work towards a thoroughly reviewed and finalized ordinance before seeking final approval.

115
00:19:59,423 --> 00:20:19,350
[SPEAKER_05]: While significant progress has been made, several key sections still require further review, including enforcement authority, exceptions and waivers, wage rate, labor peace, establishment of the standard compensation rate applicable to future procurement processes.

116
00:20:19,990 --> 00:20:26,733
[SPEAKER_05]: And for that, we need analysis from our finance director, who currently has been working on the citywide budget.

117
00:20:27,393 --> 00:20:32,939
[SPEAKER_05]: transitional employment period, and definitions and effective date.

118
00:20:33,920 --> 00:20:38,464
[SPEAKER_05]: Although the group has made meaningful progress, there is still work to be done.

119
00:20:39,085 --> 00:20:47,393
[SPEAKER_05]: Additional time would allow the working group to complete its review thoughtfully and provide the council with well-vetted recommendations.

120
00:20:48,094 --> 00:21:03,062
[SPEAKER_05]: For these reasons, we respectfully request that the City Council defer final action on the ordinance and provide the working group with additional time to complete its review and present any final amendments for consideration.

121
00:21:03,783 --> 00:21:11,587
[SPEAKER_05]: Thank you for your consideration of this request and for your continued commitment to a thorough and collaborative legislative process.

122
00:21:12,207 --> 00:21:14,469
[SPEAKER_05]: And that is sincerely from myself,

123
00:21:15,149 --> 00:21:22,231
[SPEAKER_05]: the former facilities director of the city of Bedford and from Fiona Maxwell, our chief procurement officer.

124
00:21:25,932 --> 00:21:26,572
[SPEAKER_02]: Thank you, Paul.

125
00:21:28,452 --> 00:21:31,173
[SPEAKER_02]: And, you know, I have appreciated the discussions we've had.

126
00:21:31,193 --> 00:21:37,455
[SPEAKER_02]: I do think, you know, I am proposing some two minor changes to the ordinance tonight that I think we can agree on.

127
00:21:37,475 --> 00:21:42,116
[SPEAKER_02]: There were a number of other changes in our discussions that, you know,

128
00:21:44,407 --> 00:21:48,848
[SPEAKER_02]: I think the administration would like to see some different language in this ordinance.

129
00:21:50,188 --> 00:21:57,329
[SPEAKER_02]: I don't necessarily think that whatever comes out of those discussions will necessarily be a joint recommendation that includes myself.

130
00:21:59,030 --> 00:22:02,110
[SPEAKER_02]: That is subject to further discussion.

131
00:22:03,030 --> 00:22:08,251
[SPEAKER_02]: My personal perspective is that we are now in month seven of considering this ordinance.

132
00:22:08,971 --> 00:22:12,152
[SPEAKER_02]: And I believe that we have an ordinance that is

133
00:22:14,120 --> 00:22:32,334
[SPEAKER_02]: strong that will meet the purposes and intent of the city council and that we can approve tonight and that we can continue to discuss the administration's proposed changes and that those can come back before the council to amend this ordinance in the future as the administration sees fit.

134
00:22:32,454 --> 00:22:38,398
[SPEAKER_02]: And I am more than happy to continue discussing those proposed differences.

135
00:22:38,759 --> 00:22:42,702
[SPEAKER_02]: In some cases, I think differences of policy with the administration

136
00:22:43,645 --> 00:22:48,147
[SPEAKER_02]: But I also believe that for a number of reasons we should move forward tonight.

137
00:22:48,987 --> 00:22:49,948
[SPEAKER_02]: So that's my perspective.

138
00:22:49,988 --> 00:22:52,029
[SPEAKER_02]: It differs from the perspective of the administration.

139
00:22:53,169 --> 00:23:01,713
[SPEAKER_02]: With that, I'm happy to go to counselors for their perspective on how we should move forward now that you've heard from all involved.

140
00:23:02,594 --> 00:23:03,594
[SPEAKER_02]: Vice President Lazaro.

141
00:23:05,855 --> 00:23:06,315
[SPEAKER_03]: Thank you.

142
00:23:06,335 --> 00:23:10,877
[SPEAKER_03]: I am comfortable moving forward with the third reading tonight.

143
00:23:12,929 --> 00:23:31,084
[SPEAKER_03]: I think we've talked about this quite a lot and reviewed it quite a lot and I don't see why there would be too much of a, why it would be opening us up to liability.

144
00:23:32,736 --> 00:23:38,979
[SPEAKER_03]: And if it was, I would have liked to hear about that significantly earlier from our legal representation.

145
00:23:40,120 --> 00:23:46,903
[SPEAKER_03]: So I'm happy to motion to approve the standard compensation ordinance for third reading.

146
00:23:48,924 --> 00:23:50,305
[SPEAKER_02]: On that motion, is there a second?

147
00:23:50,825 --> 00:23:51,706
[SPEAKER_02]: Seconded by Councilor Sang.

148
00:23:51,746 --> 00:23:53,827
[SPEAKER_02]: And I recognize Councilor Callahan and Councilor Sang.

149
00:23:55,270 --> 00:23:55,931
[SPEAKER_14]: Thank you.

150
00:23:56,051 --> 00:24:19,309
[SPEAKER_14]: I know we have been discussing this for many months, but for those folks who may be tuning in for the first time today, I would really appreciate if, I know President Behrs, you have been working closely and directly with many different parties to go over the wording, as well as working with the administration over the wording.

151
00:24:20,150 --> 00:24:22,592
[SPEAKER_14]: And I would love it if you wouldn't mind summarizing

152
00:24:24,072 --> 00:24:28,574
[SPEAKER_14]: where the wording and definitions that are in this ordinance come from.

153
00:24:28,594 --> 00:24:44,521
[SPEAKER_14]: Like if they come from other cities ordinances that have been in place for years or like if you can give us a little bit of a summary so that the public can have some of the same knowledge that we have because we've been in these meetings, you know, for seven months.

154
00:24:44,561 --> 00:24:46,762
[SPEAKER_14]: If you don't mind doing a little bit of a summary, I think that would be helpful.

155
00:24:47,311 --> 00:24:55,815
[SPEAKER_02]: Sure, and I really encourage residents to go back to look at the committee of the whole meetings and the meeting for first reading that we held.

156
00:24:56,556 --> 00:24:59,937
[SPEAKER_02]: There was some really great discussions from counselors.

157
00:25:00,418 --> 00:25:07,961
[SPEAKER_02]: We heard from Peter Enrich, who's one of the, you know, Northeastern professor and has worked on a lot of this municipal law.

158
00:25:09,782 --> 00:25:14,948
[SPEAKER_02]: This is a similar ordinance to ordinances that we see in Boston, Cambridge, Somerville.

159
00:25:16,390 --> 00:25:20,354
[SPEAKER_02]: Much of the language comes from those different ordinances.

160
00:25:20,594 --> 00:25:29,364
[SPEAKER_02]: There are some changes, some, I would dare say, improvements over the language that we see in Boston, Cambridge, and Somerville, but by and large,

161
00:25:29,925 --> 00:25:34,766
[SPEAKER_02]: These are, this is similar policy to what other communities have implemented.

162
00:25:35,666 --> 00:25:37,827
[SPEAKER_02]: It takes pieces from each of those ordinances.

163
00:25:38,287 --> 00:25:59,612
[SPEAKER_02]: It also, it references state and, well, it originally was state, but it references some federal standards and some local standards in the city of Boston in terms of determining the wage rate, referencing contracts for janitorial services in, both for federal contracts and for,

164
00:26:00,872 --> 00:26:01,773
[SPEAKER_02]: the city of Boston.

165
00:26:02,333 --> 00:26:05,474
[SPEAKER_02]: So that is a very short summary of where all of this comes from.

166
00:26:06,575 --> 00:26:15,518
[SPEAKER_02]: You know, part of the history here is that the vast majority of services that cities and towns in Massachusetts procure are

167
00:26:17,175 --> 00:26:18,235
[SPEAKER_02]: subject to prevailing wage.

168
00:26:18,996 --> 00:26:25,439
[SPEAKER_02]: And these services, janitorial and security services, municipalities were exempted from prevailing wage schedules.

169
00:26:26,699 --> 00:26:29,220
[SPEAKER_02]: And, you know, that's because of austerity.

170
00:26:29,580 --> 00:26:32,822
[SPEAKER_02]: It's because cities and towns have been squeezed.

171
00:26:33,542 --> 00:26:37,464
[SPEAKER_02]: And I just don't think when our budgets are squeezed that we should start with the

172
00:26:38,264 --> 00:26:48,636
[SPEAKER_02]: workers who are most vulnerable and those workers who are doing work that we've decided we used to pay people to work for the city for, we've decided to contract out to a private contractor.

173
00:26:49,897 --> 00:26:53,901
[SPEAKER_02]: That's not the place that we should start when we're facing budget issues.

174
00:26:54,022 --> 00:26:57,425
[SPEAKER_02]: So there have been cities and towns who are our neighbors who have said,

175
00:26:58,066 --> 00:27:21,595
[SPEAKER_02]: The state doesn't make us do this anymore but it's our community values that we want to do this anyway and we believe that folks who are doing janitorial and security services who are keeping our buildings clean and well-maintained and safe should be paid living wages and benefits or at least prevailing wages and benefits, fair wages and benefits because cities shouldn't be participating in the race to the bottom.

176
00:27:21,995 --> 00:27:24,076
[SPEAKER_02]: So I hope that is a fair summary.

177
00:27:24,604 --> 00:27:27,008
[SPEAKER_14]: Thank you, I do appreciate that very much.

178
00:27:27,449 --> 00:27:38,766
[SPEAKER_14]: And I just, I personally want to say that I really do think that we are in a moment in America where we are facing the largest gap in inequality.

179
00:27:39,666 --> 00:27:41,829
[SPEAKER_14]: that I believe has ever been recorded.

180
00:27:42,330 --> 00:27:46,235
[SPEAKER_14]: And it is not just bad for the people at the bottom.

181
00:27:46,435 --> 00:27:47,857
[SPEAKER_14]: It is bad for democracy.

182
00:27:47,877 --> 00:27:49,840
[SPEAKER_14]: It is bad for all of us.

183
00:27:50,841 --> 00:27:56,870
[SPEAKER_14]: And I think that as a city, I know that this city for many years was one of the few places

184
00:27:57,430 --> 00:28:01,492
[SPEAKER_14]: where working class people could buy a home and have a comfortable life.

185
00:28:01,992 --> 00:28:21,182
[SPEAKER_14]: And I know that those people value unions and they value supporting union labor and they value supporting people who are doing the hard work that does not pay that well, but working hard, those people should be able to maintain their jobs when it is our own city.

186
00:28:21,642 --> 00:28:22,283
[SPEAKER_14]: hiring them.

187
00:28:22,884 --> 00:28:33,961
[SPEAKER_14]: So, to me, this is very important, and after seven months, I just, I'm not comfortable anymore with the, you know,

188
00:28:36,091 --> 00:28:41,635
[SPEAKER_14]: the request for delay that is, well, we just want to keep, you know, workshopping the definitions and the language.

189
00:28:41,675 --> 00:28:53,683
[SPEAKER_14]: And I think, you know, we can always revise this ordinance, but I feel very strongly that this is the values of our city and that we should really be taking action on this.

190
00:28:53,763 --> 00:28:56,284
[SPEAKER_14]: So I am in favor and I will be voting yes.

191
00:28:56,344 --> 00:28:56,684
[SPEAKER_14]: Thank you.

192
00:28:58,786 --> 00:29:00,467
[SPEAKER_02]: Thank you, Councillor Kiley and Councillor Singh.

193
00:29:01,554 --> 00:29:02,556
[SPEAKER_20]: Thank you, President Behrs.

194
00:29:03,337 --> 00:29:09,426
[SPEAKER_20]: I mean, I think I was going to say period to everything you said.

195
00:29:12,491 --> 00:29:15,937
[SPEAKER_20]: We truly, we truly, it's mind boggling to me.

196
00:29:16,802 --> 00:29:33,432
[SPEAKER_20]: that in a city that has purported to support unions, to support workers, it's something that I was taught from when I was really young, that unions built Medford, that the working class built the city, and that we should stand up for them.

197
00:29:33,452 --> 00:29:38,055
[SPEAKER_20]: It does become mind-boggling to me at some point that

198
00:29:38,716 --> 00:29:45,368
[SPEAKER_20]: we let vulnerable workers suffer the brunt of consequences of austerity.

199
00:29:45,929 --> 00:29:48,854
[SPEAKER_20]: They're the first ones on that line being attacked.

200
00:29:51,004 --> 00:30:04,368
[SPEAKER_20]: And as you noted, Councillor Callaghan, you step back and you realize that Medford's not unique, that we are playing second fiddle to a system, an economic system, that fundamentally leaves people behind.

201
00:30:06,068 --> 00:30:12,270
[SPEAKER_20]: I respect that there are different policy views on this piece of legislation, but I

202
00:30:13,552 --> 00:30:17,674
[SPEAKER_20]: stand firm in my values and in believing that we should pass this tonight.

203
00:30:19,254 --> 00:30:28,398
[SPEAKER_20]: When it comes to liability, it confuses me a little bit because we met, President Behrs and I met with KP Law on this.

204
00:30:29,202 --> 00:30:32,583
[SPEAKER_20]: to make sure that this was legally tenable for the city.

205
00:30:32,964 --> 00:30:40,747
[SPEAKER_20]: And the draft that we have, the draft that we've been reviewing on this council for months is that draft, or is based on that draft.

206
00:30:41,247 --> 00:30:44,809
[SPEAKER_20]: And so it strikes me as quite interesting.

207
00:30:45,749 --> 00:30:46,669
[SPEAKER_20]: And you know what?

208
00:30:47,510 --> 00:30:52,052
[SPEAKER_20]: I'm always open to listening to diverse opinions of policy.

209
00:30:53,397 --> 00:31:05,867
[SPEAKER_20]: I think we've had seven months of conversation about this and that every week that we don't pass this is a week that we leave workers in the dark, that we leave workers without stability in the city.

210
00:31:06,547 --> 00:31:09,490
[SPEAKER_20]: And I think ultimately that's just what this is about.

211
00:31:09,630 --> 00:31:13,493
[SPEAKER_20]: So I'm happy to support the motion to pass this tonight.

212
00:31:13,513 --> 00:31:15,934
[SPEAKER_20]: I don't know if there's a second on it, but I'd second.

213
00:31:16,915 --> 00:31:18,416
[SPEAKER_02]: I do think we have a motion and a second.

214
00:31:20,398 --> 00:31:21,319
[SPEAKER_02]: So I do want to

215
00:31:22,407 --> 00:31:30,669
[SPEAKER_02]: quickly share I'm proposing some minor amendments based on discussions with the administration.

216
00:31:30,689 --> 00:31:43,613
[SPEAKER_02]: And as I noted, like I will continue to in good faith discuss the administration's position and their requested changes and, you know, if at some point in the next months they want to present those changes as proposed amendments, we can consider those.

217
00:31:43,673 --> 00:31:51,495
[SPEAKER_02]: And I think that would be a valuable way to understand and be able to go through this is, these are the things that they want to see changed and we can then make a determination whether we,

218
00:31:52,282 --> 00:31:53,583
[SPEAKER_02]: believe that they should be changed.

219
00:31:54,404 --> 00:31:55,444
[SPEAKER_02]: There were two items.

220
00:31:57,846 --> 00:32:05,712
[SPEAKER_02]: One was, I'm trying to get this Zoom to be a little bit more legible, so give me one second here.

221
00:32:18,643 --> 00:32:30,933
[SPEAKER_02]: So one is here in the definitions, if you can see it, adding to the definition of building services or building service work, cleaning and maintenance of building not otherwise covered by an applicable prevailing wage schedule.

222
00:32:31,053 --> 00:32:42,582
[SPEAKER_02]: So this is to address a concern of the administration, you know, if there are already, if there are like someone's coming in to repair an air conditioner or something like that, that's already covered under prevailing wage.

223
00:32:43,763 --> 00:32:45,204
[SPEAKER_02]: And then the other item is,

224
00:32:46,822 --> 00:33:04,214
[SPEAKER_02]: In the enforcement section, there was a, the section 943, subsection 2, which is that this designated city department may, in conjunction with the solicitor and in accordance with powers, issue subpoenas, compel attendance of witnesses, require the production of evidence.

225
00:33:05,495 --> 00:33:13,921
[SPEAKER_02]: And it was the opinion of the administration that these are not powers that the city has and that they're still within the enforcement section here.

226
00:33:15,462 --> 00:33:38,747
[SPEAKER_02]: that the ordinance can be enforced by Chapter 40, Section 21D, so fines amount of $300 if there's a violation, filing complaints and forwarding complaints to pertinent state and federal agencies, and reviewing ongoing contract and payments and potential ineligibility for future contracts.

227
00:33:39,027 --> 00:33:42,747
[SPEAKER_02]: So, that's the proposed change there under the review.

228
00:33:43,728 --> 00:33:45,168
[SPEAKER_02]: The rest of it would remain

229
00:33:45,848 --> 00:33:49,649
[SPEAKER_02]: The same under enforcement except for that one subsection.

230
00:33:51,449 --> 00:33:52,109
[SPEAKER_02]: Counselor Sang.

231
00:33:53,450 --> 00:33:58,150
[SPEAKER_20]: I just, just for future legal reasons, I just want to be clear.

232
00:33:58,951 --> 00:34:06,752
[SPEAKER_20]: Your understanding of the second amendment is that the powers connected to it are already contained in the section above?

233
00:34:07,672 --> 00:34:10,253
[SPEAKER_20]: Or were, were the other section that you showed us?

234
00:34:12,123 --> 00:34:19,148
[SPEAKER_02]: more that the powers, like the city does not have the authority to issue subpoenas or compel the testimony and attendance of witnesses.

235
00:34:19,208 --> 00:34:30,516
[SPEAKER_02]: So there are other, more that I was noting that there are other avenues, many other avenues for enforcement, but that specific review section, specifically reviewing a complaint,

236
00:34:32,547 --> 00:34:37,890
[SPEAKER_02]: that the city doesn't actually really have the authority to do those things, at least that was what council presented.

237
00:34:39,171 --> 00:34:50,117
[SPEAKER_02]: The city would still be required to review all complaints and request to inspect documentation and further answer review and could still find

238
00:34:51,275 --> 00:35:02,638
[SPEAKER_02]: that they're violating the ordinance and use the civil disposition fines or refer that violation to a state or federal agency and review eligibility for the ongoing and future contract.

239
00:35:02,878 --> 00:35:03,138
[SPEAKER_20]: I see.

240
00:35:05,779 --> 00:35:09,920
[SPEAKER_20]: And that, you mentioned that came from administration, did it come from KPL as well?

241
00:35:10,540 --> 00:35:10,820
[SPEAKER_20]: Yes.

242
00:35:10,960 --> 00:35:11,200
[SPEAKER_20]: Okay.

243
00:35:12,721 --> 00:35:19,943
[SPEAKER_02]: Yeah, these are the two changes that seem to be out of, coming out of those meetings to be,

244
00:35:21,099 --> 00:35:26,784
[SPEAKER_02]: largely reflecting the existing conditions.

245
00:35:27,525 --> 00:35:44,019
[SPEAKER_02]: So not necessarily including an expectation in the enforcement section that can't be met and also making it clear this applies to the services of cleaning and building and maintenance of buildings and security guard services but not to services that are already covered under the prevailing wage.

246
00:35:49,032 --> 00:35:51,935
[SPEAKER_02]: Are there any more questions from members of the council at this time?

247
00:35:51,955 --> 00:35:53,936
[SPEAKER_02]: All right.

248
00:35:54,257 --> 00:35:57,199
[SPEAKER_02]: We will open it up to members of the public.

249
00:35:57,440 --> 00:36:02,524
[SPEAKER_02]: I don't know who, if you'd like to speak, Rama, or if members of 32BJSCI, you would like to speak.

250
00:36:09,190 --> 00:36:09,510
[SPEAKER_02]: Thank you.

251
00:36:09,530 --> 00:36:11,492
[SPEAKER_02]: If you could provide your name and you'll have about three minutes.

252
00:36:13,679 --> 00:36:16,901
[SPEAKER_17]: Well, thank you for having given me the opportunity to speak.

253
00:36:18,822 --> 00:36:29,090
[SPEAKER_17]: My name is Kevin Bruteau and I'm excited to speak today about the opportunity to improve working conditions for building service workers in Medford.

254
00:36:31,051 --> 00:36:34,854
[SPEAKER_17]: And I am here to support President Barrett's standard compensation ordinance.

255
00:36:35,474 --> 00:36:41,859
[SPEAKER_17]: This ordinance would provide critical protections for contracted building service workers in the city who are paid hourly

256
00:36:42,605 --> 00:36:48,530
[SPEAKER_17]: and give workers a 90-day grace period in the event of a contractor change at their work site.

257
00:36:49,511 --> 00:36:58,018
[SPEAKER_17]: This would give workers time to either improve themselves to a new employer or find a new job if necessary.

258
00:36:58,838 --> 00:37:05,783
[SPEAKER_17]: Contracted building service workers in Massachusetts usually have no legal right to keep their job if the contractor changes.

259
00:37:06,603 --> 00:37:13,528
[SPEAKER_17]: This means workers with years of experience can be displaced overnight and lose hard-earned wages and benefits.

260
00:37:15,369 --> 00:37:22,894
[SPEAKER_17]: This kind of protection would go a long way for workers like me who have dealt with contractor changes at our work sites and lost our jobs without warning.

261
00:37:23,915 --> 00:37:26,797
[SPEAKER_17]: I cleaned the McGlynn Middle School for many months.

262
00:37:27,297 --> 00:37:33,301
[SPEAKER_17]: I enjoyed my job and I was proud to provide a clean and sanitary learning environment for Medford students.

263
00:37:34,642 --> 00:37:37,044
[SPEAKER_17]: And I myself was a Medford High student as well.

264
00:37:38,645 --> 00:37:45,169
[SPEAKER_17]: My coworkers and I had fair wages and benefits and working conditions under a union contract with 32BJ.

265
00:37:46,730 --> 00:37:57,721
[SPEAKER_17]: However, the district awarded its janitorial contract to a new company called Partners Facility Solutions, which is a non-union company that refused to hire my coworkers and myself.

266
00:38:00,244 --> 00:38:15,095
[SPEAKER_17]: The union has filed unfair labor practice charges related to this, but the worker retention provision of President Baird's standard compensation ordinance would help prevent legal action from even being necessary in these types of situations.

267
00:38:15,895 --> 00:38:28,845
[SPEAKER_17]: More broadly, this ordinance will help stabilize the building service workforce in Medford, which would improve the quality of building services and ensure continuity of services at key buildings throughout the city.

268
00:38:30,053 --> 00:38:35,959
[SPEAKER_17]: And I appreciate you, council president, for proposing these protections for workers in our city.

269
00:38:36,560 --> 00:38:40,384
[SPEAKER_17]: I urge the council to vote yes and the mayor to sign it into law.

270
00:38:40,884 --> 00:38:42,666
[SPEAKER_17]: And I really appreciate your time to all of you.

271
00:38:42,706 --> 00:38:43,367
[SPEAKER_17]: Thank you so much.

272
00:38:44,148 --> 00:38:44,508
[SPEAKER_02]: Thank you.

273
00:38:44,528 --> 00:38:51,376
[SPEAKER_02]: Is there anyone else who'd like to speak?

274
00:38:52,116 --> 00:38:52,296
[SPEAKER_02]: Yes.

275
00:39:03,651 --> 00:39:04,091
[SPEAKER_04]: Hi, everyone.

276
00:39:04,131 --> 00:39:04,712
[SPEAKER_04]: Thanks for your time.

277
00:39:04,732 --> 00:39:06,293
[SPEAKER_04]: My name's John Shabe.

278
00:39:06,713 --> 00:39:08,454
[SPEAKER_04]: I live on Summer Street in Medford.

279
00:39:09,155 --> 00:39:13,478
[SPEAKER_04]: My wife and I moved here about 17 years ago when we could no longer afford to live in Somerville.

280
00:39:14,279 --> 00:39:15,279
[SPEAKER_04]: We got priced out.

281
00:39:15,980 --> 00:39:19,062
[SPEAKER_04]: If I had to move to Medford today, I couldn't do it.

282
00:39:19,963 --> 00:39:25,227
[SPEAKER_04]: The buildings that have been revamped are high-end condos, and I can't afford that.

283
00:39:29,169 --> 00:39:29,450
[SPEAKER_04]: I think

284
00:39:30,705 --> 00:39:33,645
[SPEAKER_04]: The janitors and security need to earn the prevailing wage.

285
00:39:34,206 --> 00:39:36,786
[SPEAKER_04]: I'm here to support that as a resident and taxpayer.

286
00:39:38,746 --> 00:39:50,368
[SPEAKER_04]: And as the gentleman who just spoke talked about losing his job because the contractor changed, I think people need successorship, meaning whatever contractor comes in, those staff still have the same rights to have their job.

287
00:39:52,149 --> 00:39:59,930
[SPEAKER_04]: By paying people the lowest amount possible, you're forcing people into asking for assistance from the public.

288
00:40:00,725 --> 00:40:01,345
[SPEAKER_04]: That's not right.

289
00:40:01,365 --> 00:40:05,068
[SPEAKER_04]: The city should take care of people and provide them with health insurance, I believe.

290
00:40:06,229 --> 00:40:12,813
[SPEAKER_04]: Years ago, I worked in a campaign at Harvard where Larry Summers, the former president, said, oh, those aren't my janitors.

291
00:40:12,833 --> 00:40:13,733
[SPEAKER_04]: They work for contractors.

292
00:40:13,754 --> 00:40:16,836
[SPEAKER_04]: I was like, well, Larry, you hire the contractors.

293
00:40:17,316 --> 00:40:18,697
[SPEAKER_04]: So you do have a responsibility.

294
00:40:19,297 --> 00:40:19,938
[SPEAKER_04]: Same with Medford.

295
00:40:19,958 --> 00:40:22,499
[SPEAKER_04]: The city of Medford hires the contractors.

296
00:40:22,539 --> 00:40:23,560
[SPEAKER_04]: They have responsibility.

297
00:40:25,225 --> 00:40:28,927
[SPEAKER_04]: I mean, think about the price of gas, almost five bucks a gallon.

298
00:40:29,667 --> 00:40:32,669
[SPEAKER_04]: Price of food, I was shocked to see the other day when I was at the grocery store with my wife.

299
00:40:34,009 --> 00:40:38,852
[SPEAKER_04]: Housing, how do you expect people to live in the city if they can't afford to live in the city without a decent wage?

300
00:40:40,553 --> 00:40:42,173
[SPEAKER_04]: So once again, my name is John Shabe.

301
00:40:42,213 --> 00:40:43,054
[SPEAKER_04]: I live on Summer Street.

302
00:40:43,434 --> 00:40:44,454
[SPEAKER_04]: And thank you for your time.

303
00:40:44,474 --> 00:40:45,595
[SPEAKER_04]: I appreciate you listening, OK?

304
00:40:46,255 --> 00:40:46,776
[SPEAKER_04]: Have a great night.

305
00:40:47,796 --> 00:40:48,316
[SPEAKER_02]: Thank you, John.

306
00:40:48,336 --> 00:40:48,777
[SPEAKER_02]: Good to see you.

307
00:40:49,177 --> 00:40:49,537
[SPEAKER_04]: Good to see you.

308
00:40:56,123 --> 00:40:57,204
[SPEAKER_13]: Good evening, everybody.

309
00:40:57,264 --> 00:41:01,667
[SPEAKER_13]: My name is Joseph Casey, lifelong resident of Medford.

310
00:41:02,027 --> 00:41:03,888
[SPEAKER_13]: I grew up here since I was a child.

311
00:41:04,269 --> 00:41:05,289
[SPEAKER_13]: I was a paperboy.

312
00:41:05,890 --> 00:41:07,051
[SPEAKER_13]: I was a hardworking kid.

313
00:41:07,951 --> 00:41:09,732
[SPEAKER_13]: I worked two jobs for 30 years.

314
00:41:10,473 --> 00:41:12,915
[SPEAKER_13]: I taught trade school at Medford for a couple of years.

315
00:41:15,016 --> 00:41:19,239
[SPEAKER_13]: I'm very proud of this city, and I know there's a lot of hardworking people.

316
00:41:20,700 --> 00:41:23,282
[SPEAKER_13]: I'm also a commissioner for the Disability Commission.

317
00:41:24,442 --> 00:41:26,223
[SPEAKER_13]: I just want to tell you a small story.

318
00:41:27,584 --> 00:41:29,005
[SPEAKER_13]: My son has a disability.

319
00:41:29,866 --> 00:41:33,868
[SPEAKER_13]: He works 10 hours a week at Market Basket at minimum wage.

320
00:41:35,149 --> 00:41:40,052
[SPEAKER_13]: He pays federal tax, state tax, social security.

321
00:41:41,213 --> 00:41:44,235
[SPEAKER_13]: The government said, you work too much.

322
00:41:45,516 --> 00:41:47,197
[SPEAKER_13]: We're taking your food stamps away.

323
00:41:48,558 --> 00:41:52,801
[SPEAKER_13]: And one thing I want to say, we all want to save money.

324
00:41:53,932 --> 00:41:55,933
[SPEAKER_13]: Nobody wants to see their taxes go up.

325
00:41:57,993 --> 00:42:05,475
[SPEAKER_13]: Corporate America works people hard, and they want people to work for minimum wage.

326
00:42:07,475 --> 00:42:13,877
[SPEAKER_13]: And they tell the people, you can go on government assistance, and you can get food stamps.

327
00:42:14,877 --> 00:42:22,479
[SPEAKER_13]: And what happens, you, the taxpayer, has to make up the difference for these people that work for low wages.

328
00:42:24,209 --> 00:42:32,756
[SPEAKER_13]: And I don't think that's fair when corporate companies should take care of their help and not go to the government for assistance.

329
00:42:33,997 --> 00:42:44,305
[SPEAKER_13]: But also, I love this city and I would be very proud to see the city pay people just a decent wage.

330
00:42:44,945 --> 00:42:45,846
[SPEAKER_13]: That's all I ask.

331
00:42:46,186 --> 00:42:46,547
[SPEAKER_13]: Thank you.

332
00:42:47,688 --> 00:42:48,088
[SPEAKER_13]: Thank you.

333
00:42:52,992 --> 00:42:53,172
[SPEAKER_15]: Ralph.

334
00:42:55,475 --> 00:42:57,036
[SPEAKER_15]: Ralph Klein, Park Street in Medford.

335
00:42:57,576 --> 00:43:00,337
[SPEAKER_15]: I just want to say these workers deserve something for what they do.

336
00:43:00,957 --> 00:43:04,618
[SPEAKER_15]: I mean, janitorial services, people say, oh, it's not, what does it do?

337
00:43:05,098 --> 00:43:08,960
[SPEAKER_15]: Well, I know firsthand what the lack of janitorial services is.

338
00:43:09,680 --> 00:43:16,602
[SPEAKER_15]: My children and everybody who went to the Roberts Junior High School, the children, the parents got sick with the norovirus.

339
00:43:17,302 --> 00:43:20,043
[SPEAKER_15]: It was transmitted in the Roberts School to close for two days.

340
00:43:20,784 --> 00:43:21,964
[SPEAKER_15]: Nor did the children get it.

341
00:43:22,584 --> 00:43:24,885
[SPEAKER_15]: The parents and grandparents, I'm a grandparent.

342
00:43:26,162 --> 00:43:27,322
[SPEAKER_15]: I'm 68 years old.

343
00:43:28,183 --> 00:43:29,103
[SPEAKER_15]: I don't need to get sick.

344
00:43:30,183 --> 00:43:33,724
[SPEAKER_15]: So saying janitorial service, oh, the people with experience is what you need.

345
00:43:34,824 --> 00:43:39,306
[SPEAKER_15]: And to transfer the job, if you get a new contractor, I went through that as well.

346
00:43:39,446 --> 00:43:44,787
[SPEAKER_15]: Budweiser, when they sold, they didn't take anybody out of the Medford plant.

347
00:43:45,848 --> 00:43:48,008
[SPEAKER_15]: They didn't take on anybody, the new company, Martinetti's.

348
00:43:48,728 --> 00:43:53,910
[SPEAKER_15]: So having people move on who were experienced, that company has gone downhill from there.

349
00:43:54,950 --> 00:44:00,933
[SPEAKER_15]: You ask any liquor store, bar, that the quality of the quality beverage is no quality.

350
00:44:01,593 --> 00:44:05,555
[SPEAKER_15]: So having these people be able to move to the other company is a big issue.

351
00:44:06,475 --> 00:44:09,157
[SPEAKER_15]: Not just, oh, the lowest contractor, so what?

352
00:44:10,497 --> 00:44:11,658
[SPEAKER_15]: These people are experienced.

353
00:44:12,058 --> 00:44:14,579
[SPEAKER_15]: And I don't want anybody to go through what I went through with the norovirus.

354
00:44:15,159 --> 00:44:16,200
[SPEAKER_15]: I don't want anybody to get that.

355
00:44:16,260 --> 00:44:18,401
[SPEAKER_15]: And with all these viruses coming around on these ships,

356
00:44:19,298 --> 00:44:21,099
[SPEAKER_15]: It's lack of cleaning and janitorial service.

357
00:44:21,119 --> 00:44:24,680
[SPEAKER_15]: So transferring people who know what they're doing is a good idea.

358
00:44:25,221 --> 00:44:25,561
[SPEAKER_15]: Thank you.

359
00:44:26,141 --> 00:44:26,561
[SPEAKER_02]: Thank you, Ralph.

360
00:44:26,581 --> 00:44:32,804
[SPEAKER_02]: Is there anyone else who would like to comment on this at this time?

361
00:44:32,824 --> 00:44:35,485
[SPEAKER_02]: All right.

362
00:44:37,266 --> 00:44:43,029
[SPEAKER_02]: On the motion of Vice President Lazaro to approve for third reading as amended, seconded by Councilor Sang.

363
00:44:46,335 --> 00:44:48,796
[SPEAKER_02]: I will recognize Director Riggi before we move forward.

364
00:44:48,836 --> 00:44:49,457
[SPEAKER_02]: Director Riggi.

365
00:44:56,800 --> 00:44:57,100
[SPEAKER_05]: Paul.

366
00:45:00,421 --> 00:45:00,922
[SPEAKER_05]: Thank you.

367
00:45:01,042 --> 00:45:05,183
[SPEAKER_05]: Sorry, President Behrs, my computer was not behaving well.

368
00:45:06,964 --> 00:45:09,445
[SPEAKER_05]: I just, I understand the intent.

369
