[SPEAKER_20]: But I can't get past this idea that the proposal we were asked to approve wasn't really neutral, given the document that we got yesterday.

544
01:04:54,154 --> 01:04:59,377
[SPEAKER_20]: It departed, in my understanding, it seems to have departed from the basis of the study.

545
01:05:01,300 --> 01:05:07,981
[SPEAKER_20]: The amendment that we have right here that we're taking off the table is the thing that actually follows it.

546
01:05:10,142 --> 01:05:21,804
[SPEAKER_20]: You can't, I just don't think you can commission a classification study to bring order to how we pay people and then ask the council to preserve a result that the study didn't recommend.

547
01:05:23,325 --> 01:05:26,885
[SPEAKER_20]: I don't think that's protecting the integrity of the system.

548
01:05:26,925 --> 01:05:29,806
[SPEAKER_20]: I think that's suggesting the opposite.

549
01:05:31,633 --> 01:05:34,154
[SPEAKER_20]: These are people who have been here doing the work.

550
01:05:35,294 --> 01:05:37,254
[SPEAKER_20]: Yes, some longer than others.

551
01:05:38,075 --> 01:05:41,915
[SPEAKER_20]: They didn't design the compensation structure they were hired into.

552
01:05:42,476 --> 01:05:45,396
[SPEAKER_20]: They just showed up and did the job.

553
01:05:46,116 --> 01:05:49,497
[SPEAKER_20]: I just think they deserve to be paid according to the city's own analysis.

554
01:05:51,477 --> 01:05:56,639
[SPEAKER_20]: And I think it's just as simple as that.

555
01:06:00,053 --> 01:06:05,254
[SPEAKER_20]: We've also heard in this mix something to be said about gender.

556
01:06:05,494 --> 01:06:16,957
[SPEAKER_20]: And, you know, I want to be sensitive to it, because it's true that a gender pay gap exists, even in this state, even in states as democratic and as blue as this one.

557
01:06:18,877 --> 01:06:23,658
[SPEAKER_20]: But I find it slightly ironic that we're talking about a gender pay gap.

558
01:06:24,158 --> 01:06:28,339
[SPEAKER_20]: And then at this last budget hearing last week, we heard about

559
01:06:29,277 --> 01:06:35,260
[SPEAKER_20]: the way that City Hall, maybe even before this administration, has been contemplating pay rises, right?

560
01:06:35,741 --> 01:06:49,748
[SPEAKER_20]: Where everyone's being compared to each other from where they were in the 1970s and the percentage rates they've gotten from there, not keeping in mind that in the 1970s, gender was a real problem in pay.

561
01:06:50,509 --> 01:06:57,293
[SPEAKER_20]: And that's the reason why we have librarians and paraprofessionals that aren't being paid the way they are, and instead of

562
01:06:58,217 --> 01:07:05,578
[SPEAKER_20]: treating that as a serious gender issue, we're, you know, picking at fine details here.

563
01:07:06,339 --> 01:07:13,140
[SPEAKER_20]: Instead of treating the systemic problem, we're, you know, we're picking at straws here.

564
01:07:13,300 --> 01:07:13,680
[SPEAKER_20]: I don't know.

565
01:07:13,820 --> 01:07:19,321
[SPEAKER_20]: I mean, maybe I need it re-explained to me, but it just seems a little bit simpler than this.

566
01:07:24,803 --> 01:07:28,226
[SPEAKER_02]: I just want to clarify, don't we have five steps in each CAF right now?

567
01:07:30,168 --> 01:07:30,749
[SPEAKER_02]: Director Crowley?

568
01:07:31,349 --> 01:07:32,110
[SPEAKER_16]: Director Crowley?

569
01:07:32,571 --> 01:07:32,871
[SPEAKER_16]: Yes.

570
01:07:34,352 --> 01:07:41,099
[SPEAKER_02]: So if these were all in the same CAF, then the steps could be different based on the service of the people in the positions currently?

571
01:07:41,539 --> 01:07:41,859
[SPEAKER_16]: Correct.

572
01:07:43,145 --> 01:07:43,425
[SPEAKER_02]: Okay.

573
01:07:43,966 --> 01:08:02,962
[SPEAKER_02]: I feel like that so we can put them all in the same CAF because the, and I get it, maybe there's a couple more steps under the new system, but the study says they should all be in the same category and they're still under the current system, the ability to provide different, you know, address that some folks have been in service to the city longer than others.

574
01:08:03,062 --> 01:08:08,526
[SPEAKER_02]: So I feel like we're in a good place by just putting all these positions in the same.

575
01:08:09,778 --> 01:08:11,840
[SPEAKER_02]: classification because that's what the study says we should do.

576
01:08:12,140 --> 01:08:13,021
[SPEAKER_02]: So that's just my opinion.

577
01:08:13,041 --> 01:08:14,682
[SPEAKER_02]: I support the most.

578
01:08:14,702 --> 01:08:15,363
[SPEAKER_02]: Has there been a motion?

579
01:08:15,383 --> 01:08:16,484
[SPEAKER_02]: Sorry, I was out of the room for a second.

580
01:08:16,504 --> 01:08:17,244
[SPEAKER_03]: No, not yet.

581
01:08:17,485 --> 01:08:19,206
[SPEAKER_02]: I would, a motion to approve for third reading.

582
01:08:19,947 --> 01:08:34,679
[SPEAKER_03]: On the motion of President Behrs to approve the amendments, the personnel ordinance seconded by Councilor Callahan, we will continue discussing and take up that vote in a moment.

583
01:08:35,500 --> 01:08:36,561
[SPEAKER_03]: Councilor Callahan?

584
01:08:39,547 --> 01:08:52,817
[SPEAKER_14]: I'm just going to summarize what I understand for folks who maybe weren't here at the last discussion, because the public's always listening, and I want to make sure folks, you know, listening online and here in the audience have an understanding.

585
01:08:53,317 --> 01:08:57,900
[SPEAKER_14]: So there are three positions that are being recommended to move up the CAF system.

586
01:08:57,940 --> 01:09:04,285
[SPEAKER_14]: CAF is like a governmental system that determines sort of ranges of pay.

587
01:09:04,665 --> 01:09:13,876
[SPEAKER_14]: So every calf is a range of pay and within that range there are steps and those steps are related to how long you've been there primarily but possibly other things.

588
01:09:15,719 --> 01:09:22,467
[SPEAKER_14]: So we were requested to move two people up to remove three different positions up to calves.

589
01:09:23,929 --> 01:09:38,269
[SPEAKER_14]: in order to align with other cities, right, to make sure that our pay is commensurate with other cities so that we are able to retain people and hire good people, and we commissioned a study

590
01:09:39,630 --> 01:09:46,695
[SPEAKER_14]: from the Collins Center, which is the sort of statewide expert in many things, including charters and studies like this.

591
01:09:47,836 --> 01:09:58,582
[SPEAKER_14]: And they, we just got to look at this today, and, you know, I looked at it myself, and it does say that these three positions should all be within the same calf.

592
01:09:59,243 --> 01:10:06,187
[SPEAKER_14]: And so what we were requested to do was to move each of them up two, which would put two of them in the same calf and one of them below that calf.

593
01:10:07,048 --> 01:10:08,108
[SPEAKER_14]: And what we did,

594
01:10:09,109 --> 01:10:19,936
[SPEAKER_14]: a few weeks ago was we said no we think they should all be in the same calf not even knowing that we were then going to receive an official study from the Collins Center that said they should all be in the same calf which is exactly what we passed.

595
01:10:20,677 --> 01:10:33,345
[SPEAKER_14]: So we are now being asked to return one of those positions to the lower calf even though the Collins Center report says they should all be in the same calf.

596
01:10:34,125 --> 01:10:35,406
[SPEAKER_14]: So I will admit to

597
01:10:38,027 --> 01:10:53,636
[SPEAKER_14]: being aligned with my colleague, Councilor Zang, and being baffled, because it does seem that the report that we just received from the official statewide experts in this says that they should be in the same CAF, and that is what we are suggesting that we do.

598
01:10:54,096 --> 01:10:56,157
[SPEAKER_14]: Thanks.

599
01:10:58,679 --> 01:11:05,242
[SPEAKER_03]: Madam Chief of Staff, I will, oh, sorry, Councilor Scarpelli, I'll take Councilor Scarpelli, and I'll come right to you.

600
01:11:06,062 --> 01:11:06,863
[SPEAKER_03]: Sorry about that.

601
01:11:07,446 --> 01:11:08,087
[SPEAKER_06]: Thank you so much.

602
01:11:08,567 --> 01:11:18,993
[SPEAKER_06]: Again, I look at this in a different viewpoint because I have negotiated a municipal contract.

603
01:11:19,673 --> 01:11:22,075
[SPEAKER_06]: I've worked and negotiated my own contract in my unit.

604
01:11:22,195 --> 01:11:30,640
[SPEAKER_06]: It's different maybe with the unit, but we did a wage analysis in the community I work, and it reads exactly what we're seeing with the CAF.

605
01:11:30,700 --> 01:11:35,403
[SPEAKER_06]: When it came to an equity piece, you're looking at equity for the people that have worked

606
01:11:36,294 --> 01:11:40,757
[SPEAKER_06]: more years, they should be compensated for what they deserve.

607
01:11:40,797 --> 01:11:41,698
[SPEAKER_06]: That's why the steps.

608
01:11:41,778 --> 01:11:47,321
[SPEAKER_06]: Now, me, I fall into, we had four classifications when we started negotiations.

609
01:11:48,082 --> 01:11:55,687
[SPEAKER_06]: Once we did this wage analysis, we then moved to five steps and then a 5A, so it was actually six steps.

610
01:11:56,834 --> 01:11:58,415
[SPEAKER_06]: So six caps per se.

611
01:11:58,735 --> 01:11:59,756
[SPEAKER_06]: So that's step.

612
01:12:00,196 --> 01:12:06,661
[SPEAKER_06]: And then once it went in, then you started seeing the years of service where you fell in your step seven.

613
01:12:06,741 --> 01:12:08,782
[SPEAKER_06]: So I'm 18 years of service.

614
01:12:09,203 --> 01:12:16,728
[SPEAKER_06]: So I fell into the fifth, fifth block step 12, which is the highest step because he has a service.

615
01:12:17,389 --> 01:12:21,571
[SPEAKER_06]: So we had employees that jumped $22,000 and we celebrated that as

616
01:12:26,700 --> 01:12:27,140
[SPEAKER_06]: colleagues.

617
01:12:27,841 --> 01:12:31,442
[SPEAKER_06]: I think that's important because everybody got what they deserved.

618
01:12:31,522 --> 01:12:33,563
[SPEAKER_06]: And I think that's what this whole intent was, correct?

619
01:12:33,943 --> 01:12:38,865
[SPEAKER_06]: Why we actually asked for this and why the city went forward with this, the administration went forward with this.

620
01:12:38,885 --> 01:12:51,771
[SPEAKER_06]: So I don't see where lining everybody in the same calf, the position, the position goes to the calf and then the steps go for the individual.

621
01:12:53,171 --> 01:12:54,072
[SPEAKER_06]: This isn't, to me, it's,

622
01:12:55,080 --> 01:13:10,024
[SPEAKER_06]: When I met with our attorneys that were negotiating on our behalf and then with the city's attorneys that went through this process, there was never any questions on that end that I'm hearing from our end.

623
01:13:10,424 --> 01:13:11,504
[SPEAKER_06]: So that's what's so confusing.

624
01:13:11,544 --> 01:13:18,246
[SPEAKER_06]: And again, it would be a lot easier if I had this question and I went over to that corner office and said, quick question.

625
01:13:18,506 --> 01:13:21,967
[SPEAKER_06]: This is what I got from our HR director who's not

626
01:13:24,485 --> 01:13:29,748
[SPEAKER_06]: legally poised to answer any questions legally, but we don't have that.

627
01:13:30,628 --> 01:13:42,434
[SPEAKER_06]: So again, I just highlight another reason why that position of the city solicitor is so important, but I would move forward with what my colleagues have stressed that we line everybody up in the same calf.

628
01:13:42,494 --> 01:13:47,277
[SPEAKER_06]: And again, for the community, this isn't hundreds of thousands of dollars that we're shifting here.

629
01:13:47,697 --> 01:13:48,697
[SPEAKER_06]: This is a couple of dollars.

630
01:13:48,777 --> 01:13:52,239
[SPEAKER_06]: It's not, this isn't crazy saying that we're going to jeopardize our budget now.

631
01:13:52,259 --> 01:13:53,700
[SPEAKER_06]: I want everybody in the community to understand this.

632
01:13:54,100 --> 01:14:06,656
[SPEAKER_06]: it's only maybe a couple of thousand dollars nothing that's going to be that drastic that was saying well we're going to lose this we're going to lose that i don't think this is a heavy lift so with that thank you madam vice chair

633
01:14:08,914 --> 01:14:09,715
[SPEAKER_03]: You're so welcome.

634
01:14:10,535 --> 01:14:13,898
[SPEAKER_03]: I forget which number that mic is.

635
01:14:13,998 --> 01:14:14,479
[SPEAKER_03]: What is that?

636
01:14:14,619 --> 01:14:15,119
[SPEAKER_03]: That's nine.

637
01:14:15,600 --> 01:14:16,180
[SPEAKER_03]: Thank you.

638
01:14:18,322 --> 01:14:19,063
[SPEAKER_01]: Madam Chief of Staff.

639
01:14:19,223 --> 01:14:19,463
[SPEAKER_01]: Yes.

640
01:14:19,663 --> 01:14:20,144
[SPEAKER_01]: Thank you.

641
01:14:20,164 --> 01:14:23,807
[SPEAKER_01]: I appreciate that, Chair Lazaro.

642
01:14:23,827 --> 01:14:25,728
[SPEAKER_01]: So just as a quick question.

643
01:14:28,887 --> 01:14:31,288
[SPEAKER_01]: Some of these things have already been said, but if I may.

644
01:14:32,409 --> 01:14:37,352
[SPEAKER_01]: This is an interim step that we're attempting to take with the classification and compensation adjustment.

645
01:14:37,932 --> 01:14:45,916
[SPEAKER_01]: As has been presented, this is something that we're trying to do before we have the opportunity to do a full implementation of what is before you all.

646
01:14:46,537 --> 01:14:56,342
[SPEAKER_01]: The information that was contained in the communication that was sent by Director Crowley is the same scale and same groupings that was sent

647
01:14:56,822 --> 01:14:58,603
[SPEAKER_01]: when you all receive the job description.

648
01:14:58,703 --> 01:15:03,345
[SPEAKER_01]: So this information has kind of always been there.

649
01:15:04,246 --> 01:15:08,068
[SPEAKER_01]: I know that was a lot of information, but this information has always been there.

650
01:15:08,148 --> 01:15:21,255
[SPEAKER_01]: We don't deny that they're all proposed as group D. The difference here is we are taking a group of department heads that we have identified as especially

651
01:15:27,090 --> 01:15:27,875
[SPEAKER_01]: as especially.

652
01:15:30,177 --> 01:15:33,920
[SPEAKER_01]: wrong on the scale at this point in time, and we're pulling them out.

653
01:15:34,640 --> 01:15:47,169
[SPEAKER_01]: And by doing so, there are other positions and other people, not people, because this isn't about people, other positions that are in the CAF system that probably need some review as well.

654
01:15:47,770 --> 01:15:50,011
[SPEAKER_01]: And we've stated that in this process.

655
01:15:50,112 --> 01:15:57,277
[SPEAKER_01]: We've indicated that this is specific to department heads right now, because we are taking department heads and prioritizing them.

656
01:15:58,777 --> 01:16:14,328
[SPEAKER_01]: So it's important to recognize that this change that the council is proposing, this amendment that the council has voted in the first reading, if adopted in the third reading, would actually result in greater inequities to other positions inside the organization.

657
01:16:15,889 --> 01:16:24,054
[SPEAKER_01]: Another point is, because I'm ultimately going to ask you all to maybe consider tabling this again until June 23rd so we can discuss it further.

658
01:16:24,434 --> 01:16:28,516
[SPEAKER_01]: I don't really enjoy that for you all or for, I think, Director Crowley.

659
01:16:31,143 --> 01:16:38,371
[SPEAKER_01]: There's, I personally have been approached by our elections manager on this very subject, and I have spoken with him directly on this subject.

660
01:16:38,431 --> 01:16:48,882
[SPEAKER_01]: He's asked for specific data and information, and I have provided that to him, and perhaps that data and information needs to be provided to this council to express the point here.

661
01:16:50,183 --> 01:16:53,186
[SPEAKER_01]: So, you know, perhaps, and then I think the last thing I'll say is if,

662
01:16:54,387 --> 01:17:01,108
[SPEAKER_01]: the elections manager position is adjusted to a higher CAF, it will actually result in a lower increase to the elections manager.

663
01:17:01,168 --> 01:17:09,270
[SPEAKER_01]: And I was transparent with the elections manager about that because of the simple realities of the discussions that you've all had with regard to the steps.

664
01:17:10,810 --> 01:17:19,192
[SPEAKER_01]: So I would ask that either the council approve this as originally proposed by the mayor or perhaps table it for another two weeks

665
01:17:21,718 --> 01:17:30,067
[SPEAKER_01]: and hopefully we can come to a resolution or perhaps we're still at an impasse and the council votes as it's proposing to do so this evening.

666
01:17:30,528 --> 01:17:30,808
[SPEAKER_01]: Thank you.

667
01:17:31,589 --> 01:17:37,916
[SPEAKER_03]: Can I ask you why, how, can I ask how it would result in a lower salary?

668
01:17:39,160 --> 01:17:41,601
[SPEAKER_01]: because of the way that the existing steps fall.

669
01:17:42,342 --> 01:17:43,802
[SPEAKER_03]: So he would go down a step?

670
01:17:44,543 --> 01:17:44,763
[SPEAKER_01]: No.

671
01:17:44,883 --> 01:17:46,484
[SPEAKER_03]: He would have worked here for less time?

672
01:17:46,824 --> 01:17:47,084
[SPEAKER_01]: No.

673
01:17:47,444 --> 01:17:57,929
[SPEAKER_01]: Unfortunately, the way that CAF, if I'm not mistaken, and I'd have to refresh my memory, if I'm not mistaken, based on the way that the top step in CAF 14 works, it would be between two steps.

674
01:17:58,610 --> 01:18:03,352
[SPEAKER_01]: And our responsibility is to implement as equitably as possible.

675
01:18:03,772 --> 01:18:07,074
[SPEAKER_01]: So we would have to pick one of those two steps.

676
01:18:08,034 --> 01:18:09,335
[SPEAKER_01]: And that would be the result.

677
01:18:09,475 --> 01:18:14,257
[SPEAKER_01]: Even the elections manager himself has stated that he understands if that falls that way.

678
01:18:14,357 --> 01:18:15,878
[SPEAKER_03]: So if it's not, no, I'm sorry.

679
01:18:16,158 --> 01:18:24,202
[SPEAKER_03]: If it's not about people, it's about positions, then why do you have to compare the elections manager with the other two positions?

680
01:18:24,542 --> 01:18:29,425
[SPEAKER_03]: Why don't you just give a person a salary that they

681
01:18:30,645 --> 01:18:31,026
[SPEAKER_03]: deserve.

682
01:18:31,126 --> 01:18:33,449
[SPEAKER_03]: It doesn't, I don't, I don't understand.

683
01:18:33,569 --> 01:18:34,390
[SPEAKER_03]: It's about the position.

684
01:18:34,430 --> 01:18:37,093
[SPEAKER_03]: It's just about setting up the position so that it's equal with other cities.

685
01:18:37,573 --> 01:18:40,737
[SPEAKER_03]: So if all of these, if we were told by, okay.

686
01:18:42,859 --> 01:18:45,702
[SPEAKER_03]: I can't, I can't.

687
01:18:45,882 --> 01:18:47,624
[SPEAKER_03]: Matt Lemming has his hand raised.

688
01:18:47,784 --> 01:18:49,086
[SPEAKER_03]: So I'm going to, thank you.

689
01:18:49,286 --> 01:18:50,828
[SPEAKER_03]: I'm going to go to Councilor Lemming.

690
01:18:53,728 --> 01:19:05,260
[SPEAKER_07]: Yeah, I think that my view on this is that this is sort of the latest in a more general pattern of HR issues just not being

691
01:19:06,668 --> 01:19:09,911
[SPEAKER_07]: uh, presented to the council in a very.

692
01:19:10,711 --> 01:19:16,175
[SPEAKER_07]: Comprehensive or or clear way, um, I, I mean, I, I think even even something like.

693
01:19:16,896 --> 01:19:24,402
[SPEAKER_07]: Giving us a, like, presenting a slide deck or something like that, just sort of explaining these these issues and, uh, and, uh.

694
01:19:25,182 --> 01:19:29,243
[SPEAKER_07]: greater detail would be useful for decision making in the future.

695
01:19:29,263 --> 01:19:34,003
[SPEAKER_07]: I kind of the pattern here is something something's passed a council.

696
01:19:34,444 --> 01:19:44,565
[SPEAKER_07]: You know, we've gone through several rocky elections in the past, and we've had like a lot of turnover with the elections manager and lost a lot of money as a result of that.

697
01:19:45,966 --> 01:19:50,006
[SPEAKER_07]: And so we want to retain the elections manager.

698
01:19:50,106 --> 01:19:53,907
[SPEAKER_07]: And, you know, the way to do that is to offer them

699
01:19:55,287 --> 01:19:56,367
[SPEAKER_07]: more money.

700
01:19:57,188 --> 01:20:02,589
[SPEAKER_07]: And so we go towards that towards, you know, trying to increase retention in the city, which is a pretty big issue.

701
01:20:04,269 --> 01:20:07,990
[SPEAKER_07]: And then, you know, we and then we get pushback from that.

702
01:20:08,090 --> 01:20:08,990
[SPEAKER_07]: And we asked why.

703
01:20:09,230 --> 01:20:16,892
[SPEAKER_07]: And I'll just be very honest, like a lot of the answers that we've received to that have been have been a little bit convoluted.

704
01:20:17,492 --> 01:20:37,537
[SPEAKER_07]: And I think that even just like a slightly more formal presentation to council with the administration explaining their reasoning in a slightly more comprehensive manner would really help to avoid these conversations during live meetings in the future.

705
01:20:41,657 --> 01:20:42,138
[SPEAKER_03]: Thank you.

706
01:20:43,639 --> 01:20:44,660
[SPEAKER_03]: Councilor Malauulu.

707
01:20:45,841 --> 01:20:46,542
[SPEAKER_03]: One second.

708
01:20:47,063 --> 01:20:47,283
[SPEAKER_03]: OK.

709
01:20:47,683 --> 01:20:48,024
[SPEAKER_03]: Thank you.

710
01:20:50,126 --> 01:20:58,815
[SPEAKER_12]: You know I'm trying to take in all this information and obviously getting this study about where all of these different positions fit in.

711
01:20:59,996 --> 01:21:02,077
[SPEAKER_12]: I agree with Councilor Lemming.

712
01:21:02,818 --> 01:21:15,548
[SPEAKER_12]: The fact that we're talking about them all being in the same CAF level, and then there's different steps, but no one's actually identified what step each one of them are actually seated in within these different levels.

713
01:21:16,169 --> 01:21:26,958
[SPEAKER_12]: I just, I can't see how we're saying that we're being equitable by now not allowing someone who we've just identified in the same category

714
01:21:27,698 --> 01:21:35,766
[SPEAKER_12]: that we don't want to approve that when we have the study that says that he that this person's position should be in that same D category.

715
01:21:36,207 --> 01:21:40,932
[SPEAKER_12]: So I don't know if Director Crowley if you can address that at all but I just don't understand.

