896
01:37:43,103 --> 01:37:46,265
[SPEAKER_19]: So we are getting a lot of demand between 10 to 11 p.m.

897
01:37:46,285 --> 01:37:52,209
[SPEAKER_19]: right now, especially with the Doordash and Uber Eats so much active in the Medford and surrounding areas.

898
01:37:52,690 --> 01:37:55,492
[SPEAKER_19]: People don't have a place to go to for ice cream.

899
01:37:55,532 --> 01:37:58,754
[SPEAKER_19]: The only place they have open is, I think, Scoop and Scootry.

900
01:37:59,174 --> 01:38:01,236
[SPEAKER_19]: That's in Cambridge or Arlington.

901
01:38:01,896 --> 01:38:05,277
[SPEAKER_19]: They don't have any other options around Medford as of today.

902
01:38:05,937 --> 01:38:09,038
[SPEAKER_19]: So we calculated the impact.

903
01:38:10,038 --> 01:38:14,880
[SPEAKER_19]: This will also help us hire an additional person, because this will increase about 42 store hours.

904
01:38:15,180 --> 01:38:18,721
[SPEAKER_19]: So that means we can hire one more full-time or two part-time employees.

905
01:38:19,341 --> 01:38:25,743
[SPEAKER_19]: And we'll also ensure that all the students who are working with us, they wrap up their shifts by 9 PM, usually.

906
01:38:28,642 --> 01:38:32,064
[SPEAKER_19]: If anybody have any questions to that, I can dig them.

907
01:38:32,144 --> 01:38:37,426
[SPEAKER_19]: And also, the Long Cross Bar that's just across us is open until 1 a.m.

908
01:38:37,586 --> 01:38:40,207
[SPEAKER_19]: at night already on Fridays and Saturdays, I believe.

909
01:38:42,028 --> 01:38:42,849
[SPEAKER_19]: So, yeah, that's it.

910
01:38:43,309 --> 01:38:43,549
[SPEAKER_02]: Great.

911
01:38:43,849 --> 01:38:44,089
[SPEAKER_02]: All right.

912
01:38:44,289 --> 01:38:46,490
[SPEAKER_02]: I'll go to Vice President Lazaro and then Councilor Scarpelli.

913
01:38:48,411 --> 01:38:48,831
[SPEAKER_03]: Thank you.

914
01:38:49,132 --> 01:38:52,013
[SPEAKER_03]: I am almost always in favor

915
01:38:52,927 --> 01:38:55,348
[SPEAKER_03]: places staying open later in Medford.

916
01:38:55,368 --> 01:39:02,372
[SPEAKER_03]: We have a history of closing restaurants and bars early.

917
01:39:03,453 --> 01:39:07,074
[SPEAKER_03]: But I think it's good for business and especially good for us.

918
01:39:07,355 --> 01:39:09,456
[SPEAKER_03]: And it's good for bringing in revenue.

919
01:39:09,816 --> 01:39:16,940
[SPEAKER_03]: And in the summer, an ice cream store should stay open late because it's a place that teenagers have to hang out.

920
01:39:17,480 --> 01:39:20,201
[SPEAKER_03]: That is a safe place to go and a fun place to go.

921
01:39:20,321 --> 01:39:21,342
[SPEAKER_03]: And I think that's wonderful.

922
01:39:21,815 --> 01:39:22,835
[SPEAKER_03]: So motion to approve.

923
01:39:23,156 --> 01:39:23,796
[SPEAKER_03]: Thank you for coming.

924
01:39:23,956 --> 01:39:25,636
[SPEAKER_03]: And I'm sorry that you're here so late.

925
01:39:27,197 --> 01:39:29,858
[SPEAKER_02]: We'll be here a lot later, so it could be worse.

926
01:39:29,898 --> 01:39:31,359
[SPEAKER_02]: I understand.

927
01:39:31,379 --> 01:39:33,239
[SPEAKER_02]: I'll go to, thank you, Council, Vice President Lazar.

928
01:39:33,279 --> 01:39:34,840
[SPEAKER_02]: I'll go to Councilor Schapiro.

929
01:39:35,320 --> 01:39:36,080
[SPEAKER_02]: Thank you, Mr. President.

930
01:39:36,380 --> 01:39:37,401
[SPEAKER_02]: Licensing, permitting, and signs.

931
01:39:38,241 --> 01:39:39,081
[SPEAKER_06]: Thank you, Mr. President.

932
01:39:39,121 --> 01:39:42,763
[SPEAKER_06]: I appreciate the request, and I think that we should move forward.

933
01:39:42,783 --> 01:39:47,044
[SPEAKER_06]: But would it be much of a difference if we stay consistent at 1 o'clock?

934
01:39:47,685 --> 01:39:48,865
[SPEAKER_06]: I think the 2 o'clock, it just

935
01:39:49,492 --> 01:39:53,515
[SPEAKER_06]: For any teenager, I know my son's 23, and I don't like him being out at 2 o'clock.

936
01:39:53,575 --> 01:40:00,680
[SPEAKER_06]: So for some reason, I think being consistent for that neighborhood with different restaurants, I think staying at 1 o'clock.

937
01:40:00,740 --> 01:40:02,981
[SPEAKER_06]: And then I know this is only seasonal.

938
01:40:03,962 --> 01:40:06,404
[SPEAKER_06]: If the petitioner doesn't mind, that's not a big deal.

939
01:40:06,824 --> 01:40:12,808
[SPEAKER_06]: For those three days, instead of staying open till 2 o'clock, just to be consistent.

940
01:40:12,929 --> 01:40:16,831
[SPEAKER_06]: And then I would recommend that we do put some sort

941
01:40:18,627 --> 01:40:24,490
[SPEAKER_06]: evaluation like we normally do, obviously not 30 days, 60 days, but maybe a two week review.

942
01:40:24,510 --> 01:40:30,313
[SPEAKER_06]: I did talk to the code enforcement officer and he never had any issues.

943
01:40:30,353 --> 01:40:38,777
[SPEAKER_06]: There's never been an issue, but being that there are apartments upstairs and this is something new, I think that we should be cognizant of that too.

944
01:40:38,897 --> 01:40:40,978
[SPEAKER_06]: So whatever way we go, I think we should

945
01:40:41,703 --> 01:40:46,885
[SPEAKER_06]: at least put in some sort of review within two or three weeks at the beginning of the summer.

946
01:40:47,405 --> 01:40:51,546
[SPEAKER_06]: I know this ends at Labor Day, but I would request that, Mr. President.

947
01:40:51,726 --> 01:40:56,347
[SPEAKER_06]: And then, like I said, to be consistent, I would like to stay open just until 1 o'clock.

948
01:40:58,048 --> 01:40:59,028
[SPEAKER_19]: If I may just add something to that.

949
01:40:59,048 --> 01:40:59,308
[SPEAKER_06]: Yes, go ahead.

950
01:40:59,988 --> 01:41:03,409
[SPEAKER_19]: So, Council Member, we actually had a discussion internally for that as well.

951
01:41:03,929 --> 01:41:06,290
[SPEAKER_19]: So, I think we are aligned with what you are saying.

952
01:41:06,830 --> 01:41:12,152
[SPEAKER_19]: We were hoping just to get Common Pictures approved till 2 a.m., so we don't have to come back if you want us to open later.

953
01:41:12,192 --> 01:41:16,413
[SPEAKER_19]: But as of now, when we spoke with our employees as well, a lot of them take the MBTA to go back.

954
01:41:16,834 --> 01:41:20,315
[SPEAKER_19]: And the last buses are around 1.15 to 1.20 to 1.30, right?

955
01:41:20,535 --> 01:41:22,515
[SPEAKER_19]: So we have been cognizant of that.

956
01:41:22,756 --> 01:41:26,317
[SPEAKER_19]: And our plan is initially to go to midnight and then to 1.

957
01:41:27,217 --> 01:41:32,120
[SPEAKER_19]: But in the rare cases, we were hoping that if we stay open, it probably will be just the family operating.

958
01:41:32,721 --> 01:41:35,182
[SPEAKER_19]: And we'll let all the people who take the MBTA leave by 1, 1.15.

959
01:41:35,242 --> 01:41:39,685
[SPEAKER_19]: We get an ice cream shop, so it doesn't take like one hour for us to close.

960
01:41:40,105 --> 01:41:43,928
[SPEAKER_19]: They can do majority of the closing activities from 12 to 1.

961
01:41:44,368 --> 01:41:47,070
[SPEAKER_19]: And thereby, they can leave around 1.15 to 1.20.

962
01:41:47,270 --> 01:41:50,532
[SPEAKER_19]: Thereby, they can catch up their buses or wherever they need to go.

963
01:41:50,752 --> 01:41:50,932
[SPEAKER_06]: Right.

964
01:41:50,952 --> 01:41:52,693
[SPEAKER_06]: This is hours of operations.

965
01:41:52,793 --> 01:41:54,915
[SPEAKER_06]: So you operate until 1, you close the door, then you

966
01:41:55,415 --> 01:41:59,759
[SPEAKER_06]: take 15 to 20 minutes to clean, that's acceptable.

967
01:41:59,959 --> 01:42:06,504
[SPEAKER_19]: We usually complete all the cleaning activities and everything because people, we, last order is going to be around 12.45 for online.

968
01:42:06,724 --> 01:42:06,864
[SPEAKER_06]: Yeah.

969
01:42:07,144 --> 01:42:10,587
[SPEAKER_19]: So, there are not a lot of people who walk in, it's just more like the online orders.

970
01:42:10,847 --> 01:42:13,309
[SPEAKER_06]: So, are you all right just being consistent at one o'clock throughout?

971
01:42:13,529 --> 01:42:14,330
[SPEAKER_06]: We are okay with that, yes.

972
01:42:14,350 --> 01:42:14,470
[SPEAKER_06]: Okay.

973
01:42:14,610 --> 01:42:19,154
[SPEAKER_06]: So, if we could move that, Mr. President, with a three-week review.

974
01:42:19,914 --> 01:42:20,135
[SPEAKER_02]: All right.

975
01:42:20,475 --> 01:42:20,995
[SPEAKER_02]: A three-week, 21-day?

976
01:42:21,015 --> 01:42:21,135
[SPEAKER_02]: 21-day.

977
01:42:21,195 --> 01:42:21,676
[SPEAKER_02]: All right.

978
01:42:23,558 --> 01:42:28,321
[SPEAKER_02]: And that just means that if there's any complaints in the next 21 days, we might have to invite you back and talk about it.

979
01:42:28,621 --> 01:42:28,801
[SPEAKER_02]: Great.

980
01:42:29,621 --> 01:42:29,881
[SPEAKER_02]: All right.

981
01:42:30,302 --> 01:42:37,365
[SPEAKER_02]: So on the motion of Councilor Scarpelli to, well, Councilor Scarpelli has an amendment that this be 11 p.m.

982
01:42:37,405 --> 01:42:38,066
[SPEAKER_02]: to 1 a.m.

983
01:42:38,706 --> 01:42:39,546
[SPEAKER_02]: Monday through Sunday.

984
01:42:39,686 --> 01:42:41,627
[SPEAKER_02]: So you'd be able to stay open until 1 a.m.

985
01:42:41,687 --> 01:42:44,709
[SPEAKER_02]: every day and that we attach a 21-day review.

986
01:42:44,729 --> 01:42:45,509
[SPEAKER_02]: So that's the amendment.

987
01:42:47,450 --> 01:42:49,251
[SPEAKER_02]: Vice President Lazaro, I believe you moved to approve.

988
01:42:49,271 --> 01:42:50,292
[SPEAKER_02]: Are you okay with that amendment?

989
01:42:51,303 --> 01:43:00,505
[SPEAKER_02]: All right, on the motion to approve as amended by Vice President, the motion to approve by Vice President Lazaro as amended by Councilor Scarpelli and seconded by Councilor Scarpelli.

990
01:43:00,606 --> 01:43:02,726
[SPEAKER_02]: Mr. Clerk, please call the roll.

991
01:43:04,627 --> 01:43:04,727
[SPEAKER_02]: Oh.

992
01:43:13,329 --> 01:43:13,629
[SPEAKER_02]: Okay.

993
01:43:15,610 --> 01:43:17,030
[SPEAKER_20]: I'll turn on the microphone if you want.

994
01:43:19,002 --> 01:43:22,865
[SPEAKER_20]: I was just saying, if we table the budget, we'll have a place for ice cream after.

995
01:43:24,206 --> 01:43:28,288
[SPEAKER_20]: But I think seriously, this is great for the neighborhood.

996
01:43:28,308 --> 01:43:33,972
[SPEAKER_20]: I live around there, spend a lot of time around there, would love a late night sweet treat.

997
01:43:36,413 --> 01:43:41,236
[SPEAKER_20]: I also know from living there, there's already noise from the MBTA at those times.

998
01:43:42,137 --> 01:43:47,080
[SPEAKER_20]: And which is, I think most residents have learned to live with it.

999
01:43:48,401 --> 01:43:51,083
[SPEAKER_20]: And I don't think an ice cream shop adds much to that.

1000
01:43:52,063 --> 01:43:53,744
[SPEAKER_20]: So I'm grateful for that.

1001
01:43:54,444 --> 01:43:55,665
[SPEAKER_20]: I would have supported the 2 a.m.

1002
01:43:55,705 --> 01:44:00,687
[SPEAKER_20]: to be honest, but I'm happy that we have a good deal here.

1003
01:44:03,208 --> 01:44:03,489
[SPEAKER_02]: Thank you.

1004
01:44:03,529 --> 01:44:04,929
[SPEAKER_02]: On the motion, Mr. Clerk, please call the roll.

1005
01:44:06,810 --> 01:44:07,471
[SPEAKER_09]: Councillor Kelly.

1006
01:44:10,512 --> 01:44:11,172
[SPEAKER_09]: Councillor Lemming.

1007
01:44:11,773 --> 01:44:12,033
[SPEAKER_09]: Yes.

1008
01:44:13,734 --> 01:44:14,294
[SPEAKER_09]: Councillor Malling.

1009
01:44:15,694 --> 01:44:15,755
[SPEAKER_09]: Yes.

1010
01:44:15,775 --> 01:44:16,575
[SPEAKER_09]: Councillor Scarpelli.

1011
01:44:17,608 --> 01:44:21,518
[SPEAKER_09]: Councilor Singh, Vice President Lazaro, and President Pierce.

1012
01:44:21,618 --> 01:44:23,603
[SPEAKER_02]: Yes, I have the affirmative, none the negative, the motion passes.

1013
01:44:23,623 --> 01:44:23,944
[SPEAKER_02]: Thank you.

1014
01:44:23,964 --> 01:44:26,370
[SPEAKER_02]: And good luck with the late hours.

1015
01:44:30,149 --> 01:44:37,413
[SPEAKER_02]: Motions orders and resolutions 26 1 1 0 offered by councilor saying resolution regarding the MBTA's proposed amendments to the bus network redesign for Medford.

1016
01:44:38,454 --> 01:44:49,840
[SPEAKER_02]: The MBTA's proposed amendments to the bus network redesign stated as proposal to approve Medford access which presents three options for modifying routes 80, 94 and 96 and transit connections along Boston Avenue.

1017
01:44:51,261 --> 01:44:55,264
[SPEAKER_02]: The MBTA has a public comment period through the summer and a virtual public meeting on June 15th.

1018
01:44:55,804 --> 01:45:03,991
[SPEAKER_02]: Be it resolved the City Council will inform Medford residents about the proposed changes and the public comment process and will solicit and compile resident feedback.

1019
01:45:04,631 --> 01:45:12,678
[SPEAKER_02]: Be it further resolved the City Council ask the administration to inform Medford residents through the public outreach channels of the city including social media, city website and any other available means.

1020
01:45:13,218 --> 01:45:16,181
[SPEAKER_02]: And be it further resolved that the City Council and administration work to invite the MTA

1021
01:45:16,881 --> 01:45:32,261
[SPEAKER_02]: MBTA to schedule an in-person meeting in Medford in collaboration with the city and urge the MBTA to ensure that public engagement on these amendments is accessible to residents who lack reliable internet access and to residents who do not speak English, including through in-person opportunities and the provision of language access services.

1022
01:45:33,860 --> 01:45:34,320
[SPEAKER_20]: Thank you.

1023
01:45:36,162 --> 01:45:46,450
[SPEAKER_20]: A few years ago when the MBTA was exploring the bus network redesign plan, the better bus plan as they call it, what we did as a council was we sat down together.

1024
01:45:46,470 --> 01:45:55,557
[SPEAKER_20]: We had, I think, a committee of the whole over the summer where residents were able to send us feedback for the MBTA that we then passed along to the MBTA.

1025
01:45:56,037 --> 01:46:03,323
[SPEAKER_20]: And through that we saved bus route 80, we got higher frequencies on some routes, and we got some better routing as well.

1026
01:46:05,044 --> 01:46:11,568
[SPEAKER_20]: Now the MBTA is revisiting the bus network redesign plan, in particular around Hillside and West Medford.

1027
01:46:13,329 --> 01:46:26,217
[SPEAKER_20]: These plans, I think the proposals writ large either make no big effect to Medford service or actually might strengthen Medford service, although if you're

1028
01:46:27,119 --> 01:46:33,164
[SPEAKER_20]: living near George Street, their three proposals, the third proposal might cut some bus service for you.

1029
01:46:34,826 --> 01:46:37,668
[SPEAKER_20]: I just want to let residents know that this is happening.

1030
01:46:38,148 --> 01:46:41,151
[SPEAKER_20]: The MBTA has said that they're soliciting feedback over the summer.

1031
01:46:41,671 --> 01:46:47,496
[SPEAKER_20]: If you want to learn more about the plans, there is a meeting on Monday evening.

1032
01:46:48,297 --> 01:46:49,017
[SPEAKER_20]: It's on Zoom.

1033
01:46:49,037 --> 01:46:51,620
[SPEAKER_20]: You have to register on the MBTA website.

1034
01:46:52,360 --> 01:46:57,682
[SPEAKER_20]: about, and they're just going to do an info session about what the different proposals they're looking at are.

1035
01:46:58,803 --> 01:47:14,449
[SPEAKER_20]: I've also gone through and put together a kind of a guide to what the plans mean for Medford, comparing the frequencies on the timetables right now that are listed on the MBTA website to the frequencies that are proposed

1036
01:47:15,750 --> 01:47:19,492
[SPEAKER_20]: the MBTA has a kind of like a map where you can see the proposed frequencies.

1037
01:47:20,573 --> 01:47:28,757
[SPEAKER_20]: And you can kind of go through and see on each corridor, on each route, what that, what changes mean for residents.

1038
01:47:29,298 --> 01:47:36,422
[SPEAKER_20]: I know we all talk to residents, and so this might come up, and I feel like this document might help us kind of

1039
01:47:37,422 --> 01:47:38,984
[SPEAKER_20]: explain this to residents as well.

1040
01:47:40,165 --> 01:47:48,372
[SPEAKER_20]: I think in addition, I'd suggest that counselors write in to the MBTA with their thoughts on strengthening Medford bus service.

1041
01:47:48,452 --> 01:47:51,715
[SPEAKER_20]: We have a chance to get Route 94 back.

1042
01:47:53,457 --> 01:47:58,261
[SPEAKER_20]: And we have a chance to actually get more coverage in Medford, which is really nice.

1043
01:47:59,222 --> 01:48:01,104
[SPEAKER_20]: So I would suggest that.

1044
01:48:02,945 --> 01:48:09,990
[SPEAKER_20]: Our schedule is a little busier this year, so I'm not sure if committing to the whole is the best idea this year.

1045
01:48:10,450 --> 01:48:15,133
[SPEAKER_20]: Though, I'm happy for counselors to provide feedback about where to go next with this.

1046
01:48:17,350 --> 01:48:20,151
[SPEAKER_02]: Thank you, Mr. President.

1047
01:48:20,171 --> 01:48:21,791
[SPEAKER_06]: Thank you, Councilor Stank, for putting this together.

1048
01:48:21,831 --> 01:48:28,413
[SPEAKER_06]: I think this was when they made those changes, the biggest issue was that people weren't prepared, right?

1049
01:48:28,473 --> 01:48:29,953
[SPEAKER_06]: So I think this is a great step.

1050
01:48:29,973 --> 01:48:44,237
[SPEAKER_06]: But I also think that we have a communications team here at City Hall that I would amend that if you don't mind, that we have the comms team send this out to these neighborhoods, either with a robocall letting them know that

1051
01:48:44,837 --> 01:49:05,284
[SPEAKER_06]: There is a meeting that's happening tomorrow and that in the fact that where we can find this information, whether it's on Council's site or that we share this with the comms team so they can put it on the city site so people can get involved and invested in this process.

1052
01:49:05,304 --> 01:49:08,765
[SPEAKER_06]: Because again, when we don't inform

1053
01:49:09,498 --> 01:49:14,959
[SPEAKER_06]: our residents and it comes back to us, it makes us look bad.

1054
01:49:14,999 --> 01:49:21,180
[SPEAKER_06]: So I really appreciate the hard work and I appreciate the way you broke it down because I think anybody can understand it.

1055
01:49:21,220 --> 01:49:22,640
[SPEAKER_06]: So thank you, because I did.

1056
01:49:22,840 --> 01:49:24,161
[SPEAKER_06]: So which is great.

1057
01:49:25,801 --> 01:49:27,261
[SPEAKER_06]: I know Councilor Lemming would love to hear that.

1058
01:49:27,341 --> 01:49:28,521
[SPEAKER_06]: So thank you, Mr. President.

1059
01:49:28,801 --> 01:49:30,162
[SPEAKER_02]: Thank you, Councilor Scarpelli.

1060
01:49:30,682 --> 01:49:31,542
[SPEAKER_02]: Councilor Mullan.

1061
01:49:33,062 --> 01:49:37,163
[SPEAKER_12]: Thank you, Councilor Sang for bringing this to everyone's attention as well and pointing this out.

1062
01:49:37,223 --> 01:49:38,683
[SPEAKER_12]: I think it's really important that

1063
01:49:39,502 --> 01:49:48,868
[SPEAKER_12]: We try to get this spread as far and wide as we can so that people are able to weigh in on it, especially since it will be impactful for so many people to understand and be able to weigh in on.

1064
01:49:50,289 --> 01:50:00,756
[SPEAKER_12]: Is it something that we might be able to also put in within the newsletter, be able to share that as well as like another opportunity within that grouping to be able to share this information?

1065
01:50:00,776 --> 01:50:03,918
[SPEAKER_12]: I know that won't be in time for this meeting on Monday.

1066
01:50:04,618 --> 01:50:14,640
[SPEAKER_12]: support Councilor Scarpelli's suggestion of trying to get some sort of messaging out in advance, but would also like to see if we can include it within some of the avenues we have as well.

1067
01:50:19,481 --> 01:50:21,081
[SPEAKER_02]: Any further discussion by members of the Council?

1068
01:50:21,101 --> 01:50:26,982
[SPEAKER_02]: On the motion approved by Councilor Scarpelli, seconded by Councilor Sang, we'll go to public participation.

1069
01:50:27,002 --> 01:50:31,563
[SPEAKER_02]: If you could share your name and I will hit the timer.

