1286
02:03:52,827 --> 02:03:56,693
[SPEAKER_06]: I'm just not going to get a permit, and Mike, you can't do that, but these are the issues.

1287
02:03:56,933 --> 02:04:00,438
[SPEAKER_06]: I appreciate that, but I move forward with the motion, Mr. President.

1288
02:04:04,902 --> 02:04:05,423
[SPEAKER_14]: Thank you.

1289
02:04:06,043 --> 02:04:07,424
[SPEAKER_14]: So I would love just that.

1290
02:04:07,645 --> 02:04:21,458
[SPEAKER_14]: I know we have a lot on our agenda today but just a quick update on sort of where we stand like this is going to use half of the budget that is in the retained dirt balance for tenderings in the water enterprise fund.

1291
02:04:22,839 --> 02:04:28,123
[SPEAKER_14]: And I know that we have, you know, like all of our water mains are 130, over 100 years old.

1292
02:04:28,203 --> 02:04:31,986
[SPEAKER_14]: And we are, you know, making sort of a plan for how to deal with that.

1293
02:04:32,126 --> 02:04:35,689
[SPEAKER_14]: And so I would love to just have a very, if you can be concise.

1294
02:04:35,709 --> 02:04:37,170
[SPEAKER_10]: I will try to be quick on this.

1295
02:04:37,190 --> 02:04:38,351
[SPEAKER_14]: How does this fit into that?

1296
02:04:38,451 --> 02:04:38,691
[SPEAKER_10]: It does.

1297
02:04:40,372 --> 02:04:52,398
[SPEAKER_10]: A year ago we did a water main analysis and we had our consultants create a five year plan that actually stretches out to 15 years but we want to like revisit every five years.

1298
02:04:55,520 --> 02:04:59,225
[SPEAKER_10]: The retained earnings are currently at around 10 plus million dollars.

1299
02:05:00,987 --> 02:05:12,982
[SPEAKER_10]: They made suggestions to the Water Commission to increase rates over the series of years slowly to keep the retained earnings at a healthy level so that we can come in

1300
02:05:13,763 --> 02:05:20,574
[SPEAKER_10]: do the about five to seven million dollars of water main work every year for the foreseeable future.

1301
02:05:21,475 --> 02:05:23,058
[SPEAKER_10]: And so we've funded it.

1302
02:05:23,178 --> 02:05:26,383
[SPEAKER_10]: We've and now we're just allocating the funds to do the work.

1303
02:05:27,404 --> 02:05:27,925
[SPEAKER_10]: Thank you so much.

1304
02:05:28,246 --> 02:05:28,967
[SPEAKER_10]: You're welcome so much.

1305
02:05:30,601 --> 02:05:30,981
[SPEAKER_02]: Thank you.

1306
02:05:31,361 --> 02:05:35,864
[SPEAKER_02]: Just from a kind of fiscal perspective, we're talking about spending about half of the retained earnings on this.

1307
02:05:36,905 --> 02:05:37,265
[SPEAKER_10]: Correct.

1308
02:05:37,345 --> 02:05:48,232
[SPEAKER_10]: So we actually have a water main analysis that actually shows that with the increased rate, we'll actually have a, we'll maintain a healthy balance through the next 15 years.

1309
02:05:48,753 --> 02:05:49,013
[SPEAKER_02]: Okay.

1310
02:05:49,233 --> 02:05:49,393
[SPEAKER_10]: Right.

1311
02:05:49,753 --> 02:05:54,997
[SPEAKER_10]: But I mean, granted, that's also up to the Water Commission's approval.

1312
02:05:55,497 --> 02:05:58,160
[SPEAKER_10]: every year, and they review the rates.

1313
02:05:58,561 --> 02:06:02,305
[SPEAKER_10]: And so these are just retained earnings of those rates.

1314
02:06:03,026 --> 02:06:03,226
[SPEAKER_02]: Right.

1315
02:06:03,346 --> 02:06:04,668
[SPEAKER_02]: I guess my question is more...

1316
02:06:06,855 --> 02:06:09,236
[SPEAKER_02]: So you've created a rate schedule out many years.

1317
02:06:09,957 --> 02:06:13,659
[SPEAKER_02]: If the Water and Sewer Commission approves that every year, you're feeling good.

1318
02:06:13,999 --> 02:06:27,266
[SPEAKER_10]: Then we will have enough money to fund all the projects that we need to do over the next 15 years with, and then at the end of those 15 years, we'll still have a very healthy balance that will never be dipping below.

1319
02:06:27,326 --> 02:06:29,448
[SPEAKER_10]: We'll never go down to like 2 million or 4 million.

1320
02:06:29,748 --> 02:06:33,510
[SPEAKER_10]: Like it's supposed to like stay and maintain at the appropriate level.

1321
02:06:33,890 --> 02:06:37,134
[SPEAKER_02]: And you're targeting around 5 to 6 million, is that appropriate level?

1322
02:06:37,454 --> 02:06:37,875
[SPEAKER_10]: I think so.

1323
02:06:37,915 --> 02:06:39,176
[SPEAKER_10]: I think it was a little bit more than that, though.

1324
02:06:39,436 --> 02:06:39,777
[SPEAKER_02]: Okay.

1325
02:06:39,997 --> 02:06:44,282
[SPEAKER_02]: So you're expecting we'll get maybe a little bit of replenishment this year.

1326
02:06:44,302 --> 02:06:47,225
[SPEAKER_10]: I think it's replenished in the summer, like fiscal year.

1327
02:06:47,505 --> 02:06:48,707
[SPEAKER_02]: Right, at the end of the fiscal year.

1328
02:06:48,727 --> 02:06:48,847
[SPEAKER_02]: Okay.

1329
02:06:50,047 --> 02:06:52,911
[SPEAKER_02]: So we're not lopping off a chunk without a plan.

1330
02:06:54,674 --> 02:06:58,680
[SPEAKER_10]: This time next month, we'll have another $5 or $6, $7 million on top.

1331
02:06:58,860 --> 02:07:00,743
[SPEAKER_02]: All right, to work on the major projects.

1332
02:07:01,444 --> 02:07:03,507
[SPEAKER_02]: And I guess my only other question on that is,

1333
02:07:07,108 --> 02:07:14,937
[SPEAKER_02]: over those 15 years, when you say we'll have for all the projects we need to do, could you talk a little bit more about what we need to do and why and how you prioritize that?

1334
02:07:15,057 --> 02:07:20,023
[SPEAKER_10]: So in this case, these funds are allocated for water main replacement.

1335
02:07:20,123 --> 02:07:24,848
[SPEAKER_10]: We have about 80 miles of water main that's very aged, very old.

1336
02:07:25,629 --> 02:07:27,851
[SPEAKER_10]: Some are from the 1890s.

1337
02:07:28,712 --> 02:07:30,673
[SPEAKER_10]: Some, most are from the 1920s.

1338
02:07:31,334 --> 02:07:36,738
[SPEAKER_10]: And we are trying to upgrade from usually 6 inch to 8 inch or 8 inch to 12 inch.

1339
02:07:38,179 --> 02:07:41,401
[SPEAKER_10]: And upgrade our infrastructure so that they're more reliable.

1340
02:07:41,422 --> 02:07:42,522
[SPEAKER_10]: We don't have as many breaks.

1341
02:07:42,562 --> 02:07:47,486
[SPEAKER_10]: We don't have to dig into the road as many times and have a pothole or, you know, a patch that, you know, leaves a bump.

1342
02:07:47,626 --> 02:07:51,389
[SPEAKER_10]: So these are the, like, the last steps.

1343
02:07:52,490 --> 02:07:59,113
[SPEAKER_10]: before we can come in the following year and then repave the road, redo the sidewalks.

1344
02:07:59,674 --> 02:08:05,776
[SPEAKER_10]: So once we do this, then we'll come back the next year with different appropriate funds and refinish the road.

1345
02:08:06,337 --> 02:08:06,597
[SPEAKER_02]: All right.

1346
02:08:06,857 --> 02:08:11,579
[SPEAKER_02]: So this will do the underground work and then it'll be the next year the above ground work.

1347
02:08:12,600 --> 02:08:13,300
[SPEAKER_10]: Funding approved.

1348
02:08:13,540 --> 02:08:15,061
[SPEAKER_02]: If the funding is there and approved.

1349
02:08:15,121 --> 02:08:15,441
[SPEAKER_02]: All right.

1350
02:08:15,541 --> 02:08:16,462
[SPEAKER_02]: So I just wanted to make sure.

1351
02:08:18,362 --> 02:08:23,503
[SPEAKER_02]: And I guess my last question is, you've done an analysis of the water system.

1352
02:08:23,863 --> 02:08:27,524
[SPEAKER_02]: Over the next 15 years, we've looked at the street system.

1353
02:08:27,704 --> 02:08:31,505
[SPEAKER_02]: We've had you and Tim, and we've talked about the roads and the sidewalks plenty of times.

1354
02:08:32,085 --> 02:08:37,586
[SPEAKER_02]: And we know that the streets and sidewalks fall into kind of these condition buckets.

1355
02:08:39,046 --> 02:08:41,767
[SPEAKER_02]: I'm guessing something similar is for the water and sewer main.

1356
02:08:42,867 --> 02:08:46,449
[SPEAKER_10]: Yeah, but it's not based on condition or age.

1357
02:08:47,049 --> 02:08:57,594
[SPEAKER_10]: I mean, it is, but it's more safety-based, more like if there's a fire and we're pulling from a hydrant, is there enough flow?

1358
02:08:58,394 --> 02:08:59,675
[SPEAKER_10]: Is there enough water pressure?

1359
02:09:00,315 --> 02:09:06,057
[SPEAKER_10]: There are some low-pressure zones, particularly in the areas that we're currently working on.

1360
02:09:06,658 --> 02:09:11,100
[SPEAKER_10]: So we're trying to focus on the connectors first, and then once we have these main

1361
02:09:12,125 --> 02:09:20,228
[SPEAKER_10]: like arterial connectors to the substrates of the neighborhood, water pressure can get higher for safety reasons.

1362
02:09:20,248 --> 02:09:20,968
[SPEAKER_02]: All right.

1363
02:09:20,988 --> 02:09:23,629
[SPEAKER_02]: But basically, I guess, maybe I'm not articulating my question quite.

1364
02:09:24,049 --> 02:09:27,270
[SPEAKER_02]: I think I'm asking you to answer a complicated question in simple terms.

1365
02:09:27,430 --> 02:09:34,172
[SPEAKER_02]: But over the next 15 years, how much better is our water and sewer main going to get?

1366
02:09:34,252 --> 02:09:36,293
[SPEAKER_02]: And how much deferred maintenance are we going to address?

1367
02:09:36,793 --> 02:09:39,994
[SPEAKER_02]: And what will be the condition of the system at the end of that 15-year period?

1368
02:09:40,874 --> 02:09:54,778
[SPEAKER_10]: Our intent is to, we won't be able to replace all 80 miles in the 15 years, but we'll be slowly moving in the right direction where a backlog isn't going to, we're not going to be falling off the edge of a cliff.

1369
02:09:56,878 --> 02:09:59,579
[SPEAKER_10]: We've got a plan, we're actively doing it.

1370
02:10:01,535 --> 02:10:04,497
[SPEAKER_02]: By the end of the period, much of our backlog will be gone?

1371
02:10:05,577 --> 02:10:06,718
[SPEAKER_10]: I hope so.

1372
02:10:06,738 --> 02:10:11,100
[SPEAKER_10]: I don't like to look too far.

1373
02:10:12,161 --> 02:10:13,481
[SPEAKER_10]: I'd like to kind of keep it realistic.

1374
02:10:13,542 --> 02:10:15,983
[SPEAKER_10]: Let's look five years in the future.

1375
02:10:16,123 --> 02:10:18,724
[SPEAKER_10]: Plan for 15 in the long term.

1376
02:10:18,824 --> 02:10:23,127
[SPEAKER_10]: But realistically, a lot of things can change in five years.

1377
02:10:23,427 --> 02:10:28,550
[SPEAKER_10]: So let's just keep it reasonable and level-headed at that point.

1378
02:10:29,250 --> 02:10:29,390
[SPEAKER_02]: Yeah.

1379
02:10:29,510 --> 02:10:30,071
[SPEAKER_02]: I appreciate it.

1380
02:10:30,131 --> 02:10:32,193
[SPEAKER_02]: It sounds like there's been a lot of thought that's gone into this.

1381
02:10:32,714 --> 02:10:33,014
[SPEAKER_02]: There is.

1382
